  "Idea": "This research proposes a paradigm shift in studying the emergence of human-like semantic abstraction in transformer language models by investigating how both model scale *and* architectural design jointly influence representational plasticity during atypical animacy processing. While prior work assumes that larger models develop increasingly dynamic and human-aligned internal representations, recent evidence of U-shaped scaling (Paper 1) and architectural disparities in generalization (Paper 2) suggests that plasticity may not scale monotonically or uniformly across designs. We hypothesize that representational reconfiguration in response to atypical animacy (e.g., 'the cloud wept') follows a non-linear trajectory across scale and is modulated by architectural choices—specifically, that Mixture-of-Experts (MoE) models exhibit earlier saturation of plasticity due to expert specialization, while dense models show delayed but more profound reorganization at ultra-large scales. Moreover, models trained with modular reasoning objectives (inspired by SyReLM, Paper 3) may offload animacy reinterpretation to discrete subsystems, reducing embedding-space shifts despite behavioral competence. To test this, we extend the original framework by evaluating not only parameter count but also architecture type (dense vs. MoE) and training paradigm (standard autoregressive vs. modular symbolic grounding). Using Representational Similarity Analysis (RSA) across layers and attention heads, we measure the Semantic Plasticity Index (SPI) as a function of scale (125M–540B), architecture, and training regime. Crucially, we correlate SPI trajectories with human fMRI and reaction time data collected under identical stimuli. This will allow us to distinguish whether apparent 'plasticity' reflects genuine semantic malleability or merely optimized prediction via rigid, specialized pathways. The study will identify potential phase transitions, U-shaped patterns, or early plateaus in plasticity, challenging the assumption that bigger always means more cognitively flexible. By integrating neurocognitive benchmarks with cross-architectural analysis, this work will provide the first unified account of how scaling laws interact with architectural inductive biases to shape emergent semantic dynamics—offering a new lens through which to interpret not just performance, but the nature of internal representation itself.",
