  "Idea": "This research proposes a novel framework to investigate how the scale of transformer language models influences their representational plasticity when processing atypical animacy—such as inanimate entities described with animate properties (e.g., 'the spoon fell in love'). While previous studies have shown that models can behaviorally adapt to such anomalies, little is known about how their internal semantic representations evolve during this adaptation, and whether such evolution becomes more human-like with increased model scale. The core hypothesis is that larger models exhibit greater representational plasticity: they dynamically reconfigure the embedding space of entities upon encountering minimal contextual cues indicating atypical animacy, and this reconfiguration aligns more closely with human neural and behavioral responses as model size increases. To test this, we will design controlled narrative probes where target nouns (e.g., 'rock', 'clock') are embedded in short contexts that either maintain typical animacy or induce atypical animacy (e.g., 'felt sadness', 'had dreams'). Using Representational Similarity Analysis (RSA), we will compare the cosine distances between noun embeddings across layers and attention heads before and after animacy-shifting context. We will further correlate these changes with human reaction time data and fMRI activation patterns from participants reading the same stimuli. Crucially, we will evaluate models across a spectrum of scales—from 125M to 175B parameters—to assess whether plasticity emerges gradually or abruptly with scale. The study will also introduce a new metric: Semantic Plasticity Index (SPI), quantifying the degree of embedding shift normalized by contextual strength. This work would provide the first evidence linking model scale to dynamic semantic reorganization, offering insight into whether large-scale models develop not just better performance, but fundamentally more flexible and cognitively plausible internal architectures. If confirmed, this could redefine how we interpret scaling laws—not only in terms of accuracy, but in terms of emergent cognitive-like adaptability.",
